%U A397263 3,2,11,2,5,5,4,1,14,2,5,5,3,8,2,6,10,1,3,8,3,2,6,1
%N A397263 a(n) = min {nextprime(n^2)-n^2, (n+1)^2-prevprime((n+1)^2)}: distance of the primes in the interval [n^2, (n+1)^2] from its border.
%C A397263 The value a(0) = 1 results from the formula, with precprime(1) = 0, but there is no prime in [0^2, 1^2], so the second part of the definition can't apply.
%C A397263 Related to Legendre's conjecture, which is equivalent to a(n) <= n for all n > 0: if there is a prime in the interval [n^2, (n+1)^2], it must be at a distance from the borders less than half the width (n+1)^2 - n^2 = 2n+1 of the interval.
%C A397263 This is somehow "dual" to A060272 = distance of n^2 from the nearest prime.
%C A397263 By considering the distance of the primes from both borders of the interval, a(n) describes the situation at both ends of the interval at the same time, in contrast to all other referenced sequences, as well the "asymmetric" A053000 and A056927, as the more symmetric A060272 and A350100, which all focus on only one given square.
%F A397263 a(n) = min(A053000(n), A056927(n+1)).
%o A397263 (PARI) A397263(n)=min(nextprime(n^2)-n^2,(n+1)^2-precprime((n+1)^2))
%Y A397263 Cf. A007917 and A151799 (precprime), A007918 and A151800 (nextprime).
%Y A397263 Cf. A053000 (nextprime(n^2) - n^2), A056927 (n^2 - precprime), A060272 (distance of n^2 from the nearest prime), A014085 (number of primes between squares).
%Y A397263 See also A350100 (records of nextprime(n^2)-precprime(n^2)).
%K A397263 nonn,new
